                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined</hi>. some of this property belongs to Mr. Bennett—he and his wife, I believe, promised to give him some half<lb></lb>pence if he would bring the pattern out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-1117" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1117" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1117" type="surname" value="BENNETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1117" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS BENNETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I have known the prisoner two years—I have been in the prosecutor's employ three years, and upwards, and during that time the prisoner was in my employ, and paid by me—these trifling things I had hanging over my mantel-piece, as an ornament—I took some of them with the prosecutor's knowledge to cast for a friend—was had a few words, and I left there, and locked up the pattern before I left—the prosecutor saw me do it—I said, "I had no particular occasion at this time for them, I suppose I can take them at any time"—he said I could—my wife met the boy, and he said he was going to leave his employ-then she said, "Tom, you can go to work for your old master again"—she said, "You can bring your clock, which will suit to lay on"—he said, "Yes, and he had a pattern which he could bring at the same time—she said, "Yes, you can"—I did not know it—it was done unknown to me—I was two miles from the shop—it was innocently done between him and my wife—she would have been here, but was confined this morning—this pattern is my pro<lb></lb>perty.</p>
